[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Okay, back by popular demand, let\'s talk about how to train a Laura for your custom AI influencer on Ideogram 4 inside of ComfyUI. So, the number one thing that you guys are going to need is a data set. On screen right now is the data set that I used for my character. I\'m not going to be talking about how to'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'create your Laura data set in this video. If you are curious on how I made this, check out the video that is linked above and in the description below. In that video, we provide you guys a workflow with a couple different wild cards that you can use to generate a ton of different angles, expressions,'

[00:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'clothing of your character while maintaining a consistent face and body proportions. For example, all of these images here were literally one prompt that I put into a ComfyUI workflow. I set my runs really high and just walked'

[00:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'away. Then I came back and looked through all these images and picked out the ones that I thought best represented my character. Overall, it\'s a really quick, very easy, very efficient way to make your Laura data sets. Again, if you'

[00:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'haven\'t seen that video, I would go check that out first and then come back here and we\'ll talk about how to actually train your Laura. And then I also have this top row of images here, some that are generated with GPT image, some that are Flux Klein. Because we'

[01:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'don\'t want our whole data set to be just like on white images. What makes a Laura data set really good is that you have a good breadth of different angles of your character, different expressions, different lighting conditions, different camera angles. You want a healthy mix in'

[01:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here. You guys can see I have about 60 images in here. Generally, 30 to 60 is where you\'re going to want to land. 60 might even be a little bit high, but I found really great success with 60 images, so I\'m going to go with that.'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But you may be able to get away with significantly less. Ideogram 4 Laura training has been pretty easy, I would say. So, again, 60 images might be overkill. But once you have your Laura data set images, the next step we need'

[01:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to do is open up AI Toolkit. There are a couple different ways that you can use AI Toolkit. I actually just watched AI Trepeneur\'s video on Laura training for Ideogram 4. He was talking about running it locally, and you totally could. You could run AI Toolkit locally on your own'

[01:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'machine if you have the power to do that. But I\'m going to be doing this tutorial on RunPod. I think it\'s more reliable, it\'s a lot quicker than running AI Toolkit on your own machine, at least in my experience. To do that, first and foremost, you\'re going to need'

[02:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to go to runpod.com, want to make an account, and if you haven\'t done that yet, check out the link in the description to get started with RunPod. Sign up with that link and you could get $5 or more in free credits, and five bucks can go a long way in RunPod, for'

[02:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ComfyUI, believe it or not, so feel free to check it out, give it a shot. Either way, you\'ll need a RunPod account with some credits in your account. Now, what we\'re going to do is click on pods. I already have one running, but you should see a page that looks like this. So,'

[02:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what we\'re going to do is I\'m actually going to use the RTX Pro 6000. It\'s cheaper and has quite a bit of VRAM and system RAM. Training time was about an hour for me, and that was to get literally every single step of the'

[02:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'training process. Um, generally with your Ideogram for LoRAs, you don\'t need to go above like 750 steps, in my experience. But, I\'m one of those people that likes to have all the models. If you\'re somebody who is selling LoRA'

[02:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'models, it makes sense to just train all of them. So, on the RTX Pro 6000, it usually goes pretty fast. So, you\'re going to click on that, and in the configure deployment section, we\'re going to click change template, and we\'re going to look up AI Toolkit. There are a couple different ones here. AI or'

[03:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Bust has quite a few. You\'re looking for the official Ostris AI Toolkit, which is this one right here, and you can confirm that by looking at the kind of slug in the name here. I\'m going to go ahead and click on this. Don\'t necessarily need a network volume, but I\'m going to click'

[03:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'volume disk. But, one thing to know, if you\'re running this with a volume disk, is that if you start this process and then end the pod, or completely terminate it, all that data that was in there is going to disappear, so you want'

[03:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to make sure that you are downloading the models that you get from your training before you actually close down the pod. But, if you want those files to be persistent after training, you can set up a network volume, so that that data can actually be stored somewhere'

[03:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and and found later on. But again, in this case, I\'m just going to go with the volume disk. The base settings here are fine. I\'m going to click deploy on demand. Now, we\'re just going to wait and give this a second to start up. All right, and so now we can see that the service is ready to go. I\'m going to go'

[03:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ahead and click this link here, and that\'s going to bring us into the AI toolkit. Believe that the default password is just password. Put that in. Again, I\'ll even show it here. It\'s literally just the word password. So, now we\'re ready to start our Laura'

[04:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'training process. So, the first thing that you want to do is actually go into your settings because Ideogram is kind of a closed model on Hugging Face, you do need to ask for permission to use it. And because of that, you also need a'

[04:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Hugging Face token to actually train on that model. For example, you can see that this is a gated model. You\'re going to want to create a Hugging Face account, go to this link that\'s in the description below for Ideogram 4, and ask for permission. It gets accepted'

[04:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'real quick. You just have to click the button, and then you\'re going to want to go to your account here, click on access tokens, and you\'re going to click create new token, set the name for your token, click all four of these, and you\'re going to click create token, copy that'

[04:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'token, and paste it in here. Now, obviously, once you\'re done, make sure that you\'re clicking save settings. Now, we\'re going to go and click on data sets. Now, obviously, it\'s empty, so we need to click on new data set. I\'m just going to name this Vivian, which is the name of my character. Click create.'

[05:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We\'re going to go back to our Laura data set folder, copy all of these images, and drop them into the AI toolkit. Just give all these a second to upload. It\'s pretty quick. So, here we go. All of our images are now inside the AI toolkit.'

[05:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, one thing that you want to know, if you\'re using a data set that you\'ve used in the past and already have captions for it. Since Ideogram does not take prompts the traditional way that we have done it in the past and uses JSON'

[05:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'prompts instead, you\'re going to want to just upload your images, not the caption files, because we\'re going to use the AI toolkit auto captioning to actually generate JSON captions for our images. So, we\'ll go ahead up top here and click'

[05:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'auto caption. The captioner type, you\'ll click Ideogram 4 captioner. Make sure the GPU is selected here. If you\'re not seeing anything, restart the pod and you should see it in here. You can leave the name or path as is. For our caption'

[05:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'extension, click JSON and the rest can stay the same. Then you\'ll click add to queue. And so now on the bottom left, right next to my camera, you guys can see that the job has started. And if we click on this, you guys will see on the bottom here that it\'s actually starting'

[06:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to create JSON prompts for all of our images. This might take a minute, just give it a few seconds and then uh we\'ll keep moving forward. So obviously guys, the more images you have the longer this captioning process is going to take.'

[06:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Again, I\'ve only been sitting here for a couple minutes and I\'m already a third of the way through. Like we did in the auto captioning, we set it to JSON instead of TXT for the prompt type. So the first time I did this, I actually did not make that change. So I did not'

[06:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'select JSON and my Laura turned out just fine. So I mean JSON is the preferred way that Ideogram likes to be prompted, but I think if you select TXT in the auto captioning, it\'s not the end of the world. Obviously, put JSON, like that\'s'

[06:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'how Ideogram for prefers it. I\'m just giving you guys context that the first time I did the training, I did not even select JSON and everything turned out just fine. So pretty interesting, um worth taking note of, I think. And so by'

[06:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the way guys, the influencer course is finishing up. I\'ve been pounding away on it for the last couple days now. Um almost all the sections are complete. I have like one more video that I need to record for that. But it\'s almost done'

[07:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and hopefully I\'ll be talking about it soon. I\'m aiming by the end of the month to have that fully launched and ready for you guys to take a look at. It\'s like at least 7 hours probably of content, I would say. That\'s across'

[07:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reading and videos. And then obviously, you know, doing your own work is another couple hours. So I think there\'s a lot of really good stuff in there, but you guys will ultimately be the judge of that. So just keep an eye out. Hopefully I\'ll have that soon for you guys. All'

[07:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'right, there we go. So now all of our captions are done. We can see them all in here. And again, if we click into these, we\'ll see that also automatically did the B box for us as well as the color palettes. Everything here is done'

[07:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for us. We don\'t need to do anything else on prepping our data set. The next thing we need to do is click on new job. Again, for your training name, you can just set this to whatever you want. So, I\'m just going to name it Vivian Laura'

[07:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '2. Again, make sure your GPU is set just like the auto captioning. If you\'re not seeing it here, just restart the pod. For your trigger word, some models in the past haven\'t really needed a trigger word. I\'ve always set one. Um I haven\'t really needed to use it in Eviegram for'

[08:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generation, but I would recommend putting one. So, I\'m just going to set it to something like this. Again, you want your trigger word to be something that isn\'t overlapping with what is already in the data set. So, if you\'re'

[08:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'training a custom character, technically you should be fine even if you just put her normal name, but make it something unique so that the model knows when you put this trigger word, you\'re talking about this very specific character. Now, to AI entrepreneur\'s point in his video,'

[08:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'if you\'re training on, let\'s say, a public figure, right? These models have a pretty general understanding of who that person is and what they might look like. You don\'t even need a trigger word here. You just want to put the name of'

[08:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that person in your prompts back in the auto captioning that we did. So, that way you\'re essentially building on top of the knowledge that the model already has on, say, Margot Robbie or Cillian Murphy, which is who AI entrepreneur did'

[08:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in his video. Keep that in mind. In this case, we\'re doing a completely custom character. We\'re not building to the data set necessarily. So, we want to make sure that we\'re adding our trigger word here. The model architecture, you\'re going to scroll down and click Eviegram 4. I had turned the low VRAM'

[09:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'off since we\'re doing this in RunPod and have plenty of VRAM to work with. I also don\'t want to be kind of skimping out on the quality of our Laura here. For linear rank, you can leave that at 32. I\'m going to set these values here to'

[09:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '100 and 150 just so we get the most models out of our training. Everything here can be left the same even at 3,000 steps. 3,000, like I said, is a lot. You probably don\'t need all that. You could honestly bump this down to 2,000 if if'

[09:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to. As like I said, you\'re typically going to find your character around the 750-800 mark. So, anything over that is kind of overbaking the LoRA. Like I said, I like to get all my models back just so I can test against them and find'

[09:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the one in the training data that happens to be the best quality. But, like I said, that typically happens around 750-800. For our data set, you\'re going to click the one that we already made. So, Vivian. For our caption extension, click JSON. And then, for the'

[09:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'resolutions, AI Entrepreneur said he did 512 and he saw that came out really well. I actually did 768 and I thought that that turned out really well. It\'s ultimately up to you which one you want'

[10:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to do. I\'m going to go with 768 over 512 just so I can get better resolution and overall higher quality. But, he said that 512 worked. So, again, take it or leave it, whichever one you want to do. I\'m going to go with 768. Rest of this'

[10:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here in the sample section can stay the same. And then, for our sample prompts, we have a ton in here. We do not need this many. I\'m going to leave Let\'s do three. Now, for our prompts, what we want to do is actually copy the link to'

[10:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'our AI Toolkit website and we\'re just going to paste this in a new tab. We\'re going to go to data sets, Vivian, and the caption extension here, change this to JSON so you guys can actually see the prompts. And we\'re just going to take a'

[10:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'couple of these here and use these as our prompts. Just makes it easy. It\'s done the work for us. So, again, I will just take three of these. And once we\'ve done that, we can close that second tab. We\'ll do one quick double-check to make sure everything is all set here. I think'

[11:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'everything looks good. So, you\'re going to click create job. Now, just hit play. So, sometimes with AI Toolkit, by the way, this process is a little botched. Sometimes you\'ll click play and nothing happens. I think they\'ve kind of fixed'

[11:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that problem. Again, if that happens, just restart the pod and do this process again. Now, you guys can see that we got an error, which is interesting because we did put our Hugging Face token in. This one just must not be correct. So, I\'m actually just going to make a new'

[11:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'token so you guys can see this being done. Boom, boom, boom. Select all those. Create token. Be the token. Paste it here. Click save settings. And then we\'re going to go back to Q. So, if you ran into an error, this is what you can do. Then we\'ll see the trainer here. So,'

[11:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'m going to click on this and then click play again. So, it\'s going to start the process from the beginning and again check to see that we actually have access to the model. And there we go. We can see that now we\'re all good. We now have the correct hugging face token in'

[11:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there. And from here it\'s really just waiting. Like I said, this took about an hour-ish. That was to get up to like 2,500 steps. And like I said, you don\'t need all of that. Now, I\'ve already done my training, but I\'m still going to let'

[12:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this go through so we can take a look at the samples and how you can actually determine when you might be finished with your training. So, it\'s going to start off by generating the first three baseline samples for us just to see like where is it generally. And then as time goes on and as the training continues to'

[12:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'grow, it\'ll show us how the training is progressing. And ultimately you\'re looking for images that are getting closer and closer and closer to your character. And there\'s essentially this like plateau, I would say, where it really goes like this. In the beginning,'

[12:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'obviously, you\'re still understanding your model. It still needs to learn. But as it goes, it eventually finds this kind of like rounding tipping point. This is where you want to pull out your top model, essentially. Because anything'

[12:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'after that point, it kind of starts to just like nose dive, really. And that is called overbaking or overtraining your LoRA. So, you want to basically find that middle ground between undertrained and overtrained. And like I said, that\'s'

[12:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'typically going to happen around 700, 750, or 800 steps. Here we go. We can see that the training process has kicked off. Like I said, you know, even for 3,000 steps the training is about an hour-ish. But really not that bad. You'

[13:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can just step away, go have your breakfast, do something, and come back and you\'ll see all your checkpoints here. Let\'s take a look at the first samples that it created. And we can see that this is not close at all, right? I mean, it\'s got like some of the general'

[13:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'idea, but we\'re definitely still missing out on our character. So, this is that very beginning of the curve. And as training goes on, we just want to keep an eye on it and watch until we get to this kind of high point where like that\'s our character. And again, you'

[13:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'will eventually see it kind of get overbaked as well as it gets higher and higher into the training. I\'m just going to give this some time, let it generate some samples, and then we\'ll take a look at those, and I\'ll show you guys how you can actually use that Laura using the'

[13:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'same Ideogram workflow that we just provided you guys in the last video. All right, so now some time has passed. We can see that all the files for our Laura training are appearing here. So like I said, this is probably a good point to cut it. I don\'t think you need to go all'

[13:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the way up to 3,000. Your Laura\'s probably going to appear somewhere back here. But let\'s take a look at all the samples that we got. And so we can see exactly what I was saying, right? So we\'ll start from the beginning. So as we go through, we can see the visions'

[14:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'getting closer and closer. Bit of a weird result here, but as we keep going, we can see that our character\'s definitely coming through more. And here\'s where I\'d say we\'re probably starting to overtrain. The face is kind of stretched a little bit. The images'

[14:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'are just not overall that great. I\'d say here is probably what we\'re looking for. So we can see that this was actually step 1,500. But then I\'d say this one\'s also pretty good. This is step 1,000. And here is your 750. So it looks like for this character it\'s going to be'

[14:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'anywhere between 750 to 1,000 roughly. So what I would do is download all of these different files, save them into a Laura folder specifically for your character. And so again, because I\'ve already done that, I\'m just going to pause and cancel this job. We don\'t need'

[14:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'anything else here. Again, like I said earlier, make sure that you download all this before you actually close your runpod. So I\'m just going to click stop. Now the good news is that you can just stop the pod. You don\'t have to fully terminate it. Just note that sometimes'

[14:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you are still paying per hour to keep that pod alive. So in this case it\'s about 14 cents per hour like we can see here. But I don\'t need this anymore, so I\'m just going to go ahead and click terminate. And so now what I\'m going to do is boot up ComfyUI inside of runpod.'

[15:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Again, you could run this Ideogram workflow locally if you want. I have 8 GB of VRAM, 128 gigs of system RAM, and running the Ideogram FP8 model on my local system is about an hour per'

[15:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generation. I\'ve had generations that are like 20 minutes as well. It really depends on how much I have running and how much of my VRAM is being utilized. So, I just don\'t feel like waiting that amount of time. So, I recommend running Ideogram in RunPod if you don\'t have a'

[15:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'really high-end system. All right. And once ComfyUI has booted up, we\'re just going to load up the Ideogram V4 workflow that is provided to you guys for free in the link in the description. And now we see the Power Lora loader nodes here. So, this is where our Lora\'s'

[15:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'are going to go. But before we do that, you want to make sure that you actually load your Lora\'s into your ComfyUI instance. Now, in RunPod, this is typically going to be in your Jupiter Lab. You\'re going to click on your ComfyUI folder and click on models, then into your Lora\'s folder. And so, you\'re'

[16:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going to put your Lora\'s in here. So again, you guys can see that I loaded a couple different ones here. Now, this is going to come from your training. Like we said, we typically saw the best results between 750 and 1200. I just took one Lora from kind of each quarter'

[16:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of the training. So, for example, you get a bunch of different files, right? You split it into fourths and pick maybe one from each quarter of all the files that you got so that you can really test and fine-tune which one is actually the'

[16:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'best for you. So again, I\'ll load all four of those. Then we\'ll come back into ComfyUI and hit R on our keyboard. That\'s going to send an update request. And so once we get this updated flag that goes away very quickly, we should'

[16:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'be able to go to our Power Lora loader and see those files in here. So, I\'m going to go ahead and start with 600. And so we\'ve already talked about how to actually use this Ideogram workflow. So, if you haven\'t seen that video, check it'

[16:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'out. It\'s also linked in the description below. So, I\'m going to load my prompt for my character that I got from the custom GPT that we talked about and we\'re going to go ahead and just run this. And so now we\'re just going to test across each of the models that we'

[17:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'got so we can pick out which one is the best and which one we ultimately want to run with moving forward. Now, by the way, I talked about how to load this into Jupiter Lab. But if you have a local ComfyUI instance, the process is exactly the same. You\'re going to go'

[17:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'into ComfyUI models, LoRAs, and then drop them in there. And again, you\'ll hit R on your keyboard to actually refresh the page and make sure that they\'re loaded into your ComfyUI. And so, here we go. We get something like this, which looks really, really good.'

[17:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, all we\'re going to do here is just change the LoRA to the 1200 variant. I\'m going to save this image so we can kind of compare against them. I\'m I\'m even going to clear the B boxes here because we want to get pretty much the same image, and our seed is set, so we should'

[17:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'be able to just run this again with the same seed. Now, the only thing that\'s going to change is our actual character. So, this will be able to tell us the differentiation between all these models, and then it\'s ultimately up to'

[17:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you to decide which one you think is closest to your character or not. And so, here is what we get from the 1200 LoRA. So, again, we know we\'re kind of starting to lose our character a little bit. Still vaguely resembles her, but I'

[18:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'think the face is a little too like round. But, let\'s see one more at 1950 now and see what we get. And here\'s what we get at 1950. So, you can tell that we\'ve definitely over trained here for sure. So, like I said, you know, your'

[18:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'results going to be For me, it\'s going to be between 600 and 1200. I\'d probably load the 750 or 800 in here and see how it goes. But, that\'s generally how you go about training your LoRA, especially for Ideogram 4. Like I said, we have a'

[18:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bunch of videos on the channel on how to actually create your LoRA data sets. We\'ve made it very easy, so definitely check out those videos if you haven\'t yet. As usual, let me know if you guys have any questions, and I will see you in the next one.'
